text: It's just not a card for me
Being able to surgically remove stuff is useful

I like the design idea, and making it an activated ability means they can't easily (or likely profitably) counter it. If your dragon gets countered, you still get your value the next time you get it onto the field.
It's interesting that you can put a Prey counter on any creature, but it only destroys creatures your opponents' control when it enters.
The Immortal Sun is interesting since, even at 6 mana, it isn't a 'do-nothing' artifact, but provides immediate value by pumping all your creatures and making all your spells cost 1 less.
Yeah, even with no walkers on the field it's doing things
Hell, people run Staff of Nin in white/red/boros just for the draw
Exactly.
I think it'll become a boros staple, given the draw, cost reduction and anthem effect for 6.
It does everything Boros cares about. The cost reduction can be seen as a form of ramp, honestly.

Dinosaurs themselves could fit in Jund or Naya respectively. Jund has a precedent for devour and Naya’s precedent for large creatures.

I run a magic club at the high school I work at. We have a few budding commander players and others are interested in the format, but want to get their feet wet before acquiring a precon. I’m trying to build a few easy to learn and play decks for people to borrow. Some of the students interested are still pretty new to magic, so I don’t want to overwhelm with crazy card interactions. Currently I have a Bruna light of alabaster and a Heartless Hidetsugu deck
Any other thoughts of good starter commanders?
Meren, Roon, angry Omnath
Any elf legend elfball is easy to play and fairly effective

I keep a cheap elfball deck with me with my other decks to give to new players
I'm on the 4th iteration this year I think
